solutions.content:
#### This Is a really good question when it comes to building a concrete base for your Graph related problems.

**Main Concepts:**
- DFS
- Topological Sort
- Cycle detection

> For a really well excuted DFS using STL's : [DFS_STL](https://gist.github.com/sr6033/3d4a018fc0ae598616ca11f134e060c5)
> For a better understanding about Topological Sort : [TopoSort](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ddTC4Zovtbc)

I will talk about all these points in great detail.

------

**Global Variables**
> The following data structures are used.

* Stack to store the Topological order : `stack<int> S`
* Vector 'V' to store visited nodes : `vector<int> V`
* Vector 'P' to store nodes in recursive stack : `vector<int> P`
* Map to store the graph : `map<int, vector<int> > G`
* Bool variable to store if there is a cycle: `bool cycle`

------

**Basic DFS**
> This is the heart of the code, But it needs a little modification to do a Topological Sort.
```
void DFS(int n)
{        
	for(int i=0;i<n;++i)
		if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);
}

void DFS_recur(int curr)
{        
	V[curr] = true;
	cout << curr << " ";

	for(int i : G[curr])
		if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);
}
```

------

**Custom DFS for TopoLogical Sort**
> We only need to update the DFS_recur function.
```
void DFS_recur(int curr)
{
	V[curr] = true;

	for(int i : G[curr])
		if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);

	S.push(curr);
}
```

Here if we just add a **S.push(curr)** we will get the topological order in the Stack.
Think about it we will push only if we reach a **terminal node** in the graph.

------

**Custom DFS for Cycle Detection**
> We will use a vector 'P' to keep track of elements in the recursion stack.
```
void DFS_recur(int curr)
    {
        if(cycle) return;

        V[curr] = true;
        P[curr] = true;

        for(int i : G[curr])
        {   
            if(P[i] == true) cycle = true;
            if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);
        }

        S.push(curr);
        P[curr] = false;
    }
```

This code will set the **cycle variable to true** as soon as a cycle is detected.

How do we detect the cycle?
> **Lets consider the followig Graph**
<img src=https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66634743/87854395-cc302600-c922-11ea-9a54-c45e83f4e7b1.png width=300 height=200>
> **The map will be as follows**
> | Parent | Children |
> | - | - |
> | 0 | [ 1 ] |
> | 1 | [ 2 ] |
> | 2 | [ 4 ] |
> | 3 | [ 1 ] |
> | 4 | [ 3, 5 ] |
> **The vectors P and V**
> | i | 0 | 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5 |
> | - | - | - | - | - | - | - |
> | **V** | F | F | F | F | F | F |
> | **P** | F | F | F | F | F | F |
> 0 will be the **curr** first, resulting in the following. P[0] = true means that 0 is in the recursive stack.
> | i | 0 | 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5 |
> | - | - | - | - | - | - | - |
> | **V** | T | F | F | F | F | F |
> | **P** | T | F | F | F | F | F |
> Then we valuate its child:
>> **curr = 1**
>>> **curr = 2**
>>>> **curr = 4**
>>>>> **curr = 3**
>>>>> 
> | i | 0 | 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5 |
> | - | - | - | - | - | - | - |
> | **V** | T | T | T | F | T | F |
> | **P** | T | T | T | F | T | F |
> Now we see that **3's child is 1**. Lets see what happens.
>> 
``` 
void DFS_recur(int curr)                   // curr = 3
{
	if(cycle) return;                      // cycle = false

	V[curr] = true;                        // V[3] = true
	P[curr] = true;                        // P[3] = true

	for(int i : G[curr])                   // only one element in the vector, [ 1 ] 
	{   
		if(P[i] == true) cycle = true;     // P[1] == true therefore cycle = true
		if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);            // recur with i = 1
	// Jump to DFS_recur(1)

void DFS_recur(int curr)                   // curr = 1
{
	if(cycle) return;                      // cycle = true therefore return
	/*this will keep returning till the whole recursive stack in empty.
									...
									...
									...
	all the was till the initial curr = 0
	Then in the main function*/

	if(cycle) return {};                   // cycle = true return []
        return Ans;
```

------

**Complete Code**
```
class Solution {
public:
    stack<int> S;
    vector<int> V;
    vector<int> P;
    bool cycle;
    map<int, vector<int> > G;

    void DFS(int n)
    {        
        for(int i=0;i<n;++i)
        {
            if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);
        }
    }

    void DFS_recur(int curr)
    {
        if(cycle) return;

        V[curr] = true;
        P[curr] = true;

        for(int i : G[curr])
        {   
            if(P[i] == true) cycle = true;
            if(!V[i]) DFS_recur(i);
        }

        S.push(curr);
        P[curr] = false;
    }

    vector<int> findOrder(int n, vector<vector<int>>& prerequisites) 
    {
        vector<int> Ans;
        V.assign(n, false);
        P.assign(n, false);
        cycle = false;
        for(auto i : prerequisites)
        {
            G[i[1]].push_back(i[0]);
        }

        DFS(n);

        while(!S.empty())
        {
            Ans.push_back(S.top());
            S.pop();
        }

        if(cycle) return {};
        return Ans;
    }
};
```

