solutions.content:
The idea behind my solution is very simple:

* To determine if an edge is invalid:
	* if a child node already has a parent other than itself,  ``` roots[child] != child ```
	* if the parent of the parent node is child - forms a cricle, ```  find(roots, parent) == child```
* In the first loop, we keep tracking the number of invalid edge, if there's only one after the loop, we're confident that the only invalid edge is redundent.
* If we found more than one invalid edges, reset the ```roots``` and do a reverse check, return the first invalid edge we found. 

```
    public int[] findRedundantDirectedConnection(int[][] edges) {
        int n = edges.length, count = 0; // Use count to track the number of the invalid edge.

        int[] roots = new int[n + 1];

        int[] res = new int[2];

        for (int i = 0; i <= n ; i++) roots[i] = i;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int parent = edges[i][0], child = edges[i][1];

            if (roots[child] != child || find(roots, parent) == child) {res = edges[i]; count++;}

            else roots[child] = parent;
        }

        if (count == 1) return res; // If there's only one invalid edge, return this edge.

        // Reset and do it the reverse way.
        for (int i = 0; i <= n ; i++) roots[i] = i; 

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            int parent = edges[i][0], child = edges[i][1];

            if (roots[child] != child || find(roots, parent) == child) return edges[i];

            roots[child] = parent;
        }

        return res;
    }

    private int find(int[] roots, int x) {
        if (roots[x] == x) return x;

        return find(roots, roots[x]);
    }
