solutions.content:
So there are three cases when connecting a and b:
1. connecting a to b causes a cycle where b is the root of the cycle. 
2. a and b already have a common ancestor and connecting a to b means that b has two incoming edges
3. connecting a and b is safe, that is only contributes to building of the tree. 

Now, if there is case 2, with the ancestor being say, x, then it means that x - b and a -b are two possible answers for removal, so we push them into the candidate edges list. 
In case 1, we need to add the last edge of the cycle to the list of cycles. 

Now, see this test case:
[[2,1],[3,1],[4,2],[1,4]]
                    3
                     |
4 --> 2 ---> 1
^____________|
 We see that 2 -1  is always returned. Why is this natural to happen?
Now this demonstrates the use of the conditions in the lines of if (hasCycle).
If we add the edge (3 - 1) first, then when we add the edge (4 - 1), parent of 1 is 3, and of 4 is 4. So this falls under case 2. So, 2-1 is returned because 3 - 1 is not cause of the cycle and since we have two candidates the other candidate should be cause of the cycle then. 
But if (2 - 1) is added first, then when we add (4 - 1), parent of 1 is 4, and of 4 is 4 as well. So this falls under case 1 and again (2- 1) is returned as 2 is reponsible for root(parent[1]) = 4. 


```
class Solution {
    public void union(int[] parent, int a, int b){
        parent[b] = a;
    }
    public int root(int[] parent, int a){
        if (parent[a] != a){return root(parent, parent[a]);}
        return a;
    }
    public int[] findRedundantDirectedConnection(int[][] edges) {
        int n = edges.length;
        int[] parent = new int[n + 1];
        for (int i = 0; i < n + 1; i++){parent[i] = i;}
        ArrayList<int[]> candidate = new ArrayList<>();
         ArrayList<int[]> cycle = new ArrayList<>();
        boolean hasCycle =false;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            int a = edges[i][0]; int b = edges[i][1];
            if (parent[b] == b && root(parent, a) != root(parent, b)){
                union(parent, a, b);
            }
            else if (parent[b] != b){
                candidate.add(new int[]{parent[b], b});
                candidate.add(edges[i]);
            }
            else {
                hasCycle = true;
                cycle.add(edges[i]);
            }
        }
        if (hasCycle){
            if (!candidate.isEmpty()) return candidate.get(0);
            return cycle.get(0);
        }
        return candidate.get(candidate.size() - 1);
    }

}
