solutions.content:
There are two cases in this problem. Based on [684. Redundant Connection](https://leetcode.com/problems/redundant-connection/).
1. same as 684, if we find[x]==find[y] before union, this edge is redundant.
2. There is only one root means for each node must have only one parent.
For the case `[[2,1],[3,1],[4,2],[1,4]]`
```
  2 ← 4
  ↓ ↗ 
  1 ← 3
```
if 1 has two parents (2, 3), we must delete one. So when wo meet `[1, 3]`, did nothing but record. Finally, If all nodes connected, just delete `[1, 3]`, otherwise, delete`[2, 1]`, use a `pare` record parent of each node, we can find `[2, 1]` by `pare`.
```python
  def findRedundantDirectedConnection(self, edges: List[List[int]]) -> List[int]:

      def union(x, y):
          uf[find(x)] = find(y)

      def find(x):
          if x != uf[x]:
              uf[x] = find(uf[x])
          return uf[x]

      ans, N, pare = None, len(edges), {}
      uf = list(range(N+1))
      for u, v in edges:
          if v in pare:
              ans = (u, v)
              continue
          if find(u)==find(v) and not ans:
              ans = (u, v)
          union(u, v)
          pare[v] = u
      return ans if len(set(map(find, range(1, N+1))))==1 else (pare[ans[1]], ans[1])
```

