The key point of this problem is that:
`there is only one wrong edge to get to the tree structure`

There are only two condition that leads to a wrong edge:
```
1. one node has two parent
2. there is no root (formed a circle)
```

for the two condition, there is a data structure that can perfectly detect these two ---- `Union and Find`

For the first key point, there is one gold method to test all two:
`discard one of the candidate edges, test the updated graph. If it 's correct now, it means the candidate discarded is the target. Otherwise, the other candidate.`


So you can see, the main trick the problem wanna test you is whether you can use union&find to check tree-related problems in graph.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] findRedundantDirectedConnection(int[][] edges) {
        int n = edges.length;
        int[] cand1=new int[]{-1,-1};
        int[] cand2=new int[]{-1,-1};
        int[] parent = new int[n+1];
        for (int i=0; i<n; i++){
            int[] edge = edges[i];
            if(parent[edge[1]]!=0){
                cand1 = new int[]{parent[edge[1]], edge[1]};
                cand2 = new int[]{edge[0], edge[1]};
                edges[i][1] = 0;
                break;
            }
            parent[edge[1]] = edge[0];
        }
        for (int i=1; i<=n; i++) parent[i] = i;
        for (int[] edge: edges){
            if (root(parent,edge[0]) == root(parent,edge[1])){
                if (cand1[0]==-1) return edge;
                return cand1;
            }
            parent[edge[1]] = root(parent,edge[0]);
        }
        return cand2;
    }

    int root(int[] parent, int i){
        if (parent[i]!=i) parent[i] = root(parent, parent[i]);
        return parent[i];
    }
}
```

