solutions.content:
To be honest, it is not straightforward to me why would one use union find to locate the cycles instead of using DFS + coloring. In fact, you would not be able to find the cycle's nodes unless there are specific constraints, like those in this question, namely there are only one problematic edge. Thus when we have a node with two incoming edges, removing one then execute union find would give you a hint about whether the remove edge is causing cycle. 

Now, not to say union find for this problem is a bad solution, but it is not a very easy strategy to come up with in a limited time, especially regarding the trick of removing one edge first, then test it by doing union find. This really comes down to trick mastering... 

Anyways, here is my standard DFS cycle finding solution. 
The ugly: 
- The code is being lengthy and more code means more bugs. I do prefer union find solution's cleaness in terms of code quality.

The good: 
- you only need to understand the standard cycle finding DFS algorithm and you are good. 
- Overall logic is very simple once you figured out the different cases. 

Now the cases that break the graph (this really is the core of this problem, you have to deal with it no matter what algorithm you use...):
1. There are directed cycles
	a. the cycle passes root -> every node on cycle has 1 parent exactly. In this case, deleting any edge will restore the tree status, but we are asked to delete the edge with largest index. 
	b. the cycle does not pass root -> there is exactly 1 node in the cycle who has two parents. This is the most annoying case, cause you will have to find the node who has 2 parents, then remove the edge that is contained in the cycle. Now the graph is restored, this is the only way in this case.

2. There are no directed cycles but some node has two parents
	a. this is easy case, cause we can remove the parent edge with larger index.

Now, the algorithm:
1. Build necessary data storage: parent status of each node, the graph itself, and edge index for each edge. Yea I know, this is the ugly part.
2. DFS traversal on every node.
	a. when you found a cycle, process the cycle. It will be one of the two cycle cases and you return results accordingly.
	b. Note: DFS on direct graph will be a bit wierd in the sense that you are visiting connected fragments, say you visited the child first, then you traversed all connected edges from this child, then later you visit this child's parent, and you stopped right there before visiting the child again. But, this does not influence cycle finding, you will always being able to loop back to a node on dfs search path if there is cycle.
3. When DFS traversal did not find any cycle, you just return the two parent node's edge, pick the one with bigger index.


```
class Solution {
    public int[] findRedundantDirectedConnection(int[][] edges) {
        Map<Integer, Map<Integer, Integer>> edgeIndex = 
            new HashMap<>();
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> parent = new HashMap<>();
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> graph = new HashMap<>();
        int oddNode = -1;

        for (int i = 0; i < edges.length; i++) {
            int[] e = edges[i];

            // graph.
            List<Integer> tmp = graph.getOrDefault(e[0], 
                                    new ArrayList<>());
            tmp.add(e[1]);
            graph.put(e[0], tmp);

            // Parent status.
            tmp = parent.getOrDefault(e[1], 
                        new ArrayList<>());
            tmp.add(e[0]);
            if (tmp.size() > 1) oddNode = e[1];
            parent.put(e[1], tmp);

            // edge Index.
            Map<Integer, Integer> tmp2 =
                edgeIndex.getOrDefault(e[0], new HashMap<>());
            tmp2.put(e[1], i);
            edgeIndex.put(e[0], tmp2);
        }

        List<Integer> cycle = new ArrayList<>();
        int n = 1001;
        int[] stat = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (stat[i] != 0) continue;

            dfs(i, graph, stat, new ArrayList<>(), cycle);

            if (cycle.size() == 0) {
                continue;
            } else {
                // found cycle.
                int maxEdgeInd = 0;
                int twinInEdgeNode = -1;
                int cLen = cycle.size();
                Set<Integer> cycleSet = new HashSet<>();
                for (int c = 0; c < cLen; c++) {
                    int s = cycle.get(c);
                    int t = cycle.get((c + 1) % cLen);

                    // Cycle did not pass root.
                    if (parent.get(s).size() == 2) {
                        twinInEdgeNode = s;
                    }

                    cycleSet.add(s);
                    maxEdgeInd = Math.max(maxEdgeInd, 
                                edgeIndex.get(s).get(t));
                }

                // Cycle pass root, return maxInd edge.
                if (twinInEdgeNode == -1) return edges[maxEdgeInd];

                // Cycle did not pass root.
                int a = parent.get(twinInEdgeNode).get(0);
                int b = parent.get(twinInEdgeNode).get(1);
                int ai = edgeIndex.get(a).get(twinInEdgeNode);
                int bi = edgeIndex.get(b).get(twinInEdgeNode);

                return cycleSet.contains(a) ? edges[ai] : edges[bi];
            }
        }

        // visited some black node twice.
        int a = parent.get(oddNode).get(0);
        int b = parent.get(oddNode).get(1);
        int ai = edgeIndex.get(a).get(oddNode);
        int bi = edgeIndex.get(b).get(oddNode);

        return ai > bi ? edges[ai] : edges[bi];
    }

    public void dfs(int cur, 
                    Map<Integer, List<Integer>> graph,
                    int[] stat, List<Integer> tracker, 
                    List<Integer> cycle) {
        if (cycle.size() > 0) return;

        if (stat[cur] == 1) {
            // found cycle.
            int i = 0;
            while (tracker.get(i) != cur) i++;

            for (int j = i; j < tracker.size(); j++) {
                cycle.add(tracker.get(j));
            }

            return;
        }

        if (stat[cur] == 2) {
            return;
        }

        stat[cur] = 1;
        tracker.add(cur);

        if (graph.containsKey(cur)) {
            for (int n : graph.get(cur)) {
                dfs(n, graph, stat, tracker, cycle);
            }    
        }

        stat[cur] = 2;
        tracker.remove(tracker.size() - 1);
    }
}
```

