I spend hours trying to understand what the hell is this one. Hope this explanation help you guys

```
class Solution {
    /* explanation:
        Three cases before we delete one candidate edge
        1. there's a ring, and two candidates found
        2. there's a ring, no candidates found   e.g.  1->2->3->1
        3. no ring, two candidates found

        If there are 2 candidates, then we delete second candidate edge
        Three cases remaining:

        1#. there's still a ring, and two candidates found
        This means deleted candidate edge is not inside the ring, so return first candidate

        2# there's still a ring, no two candidates found
        This means we never made the deletion, so just return current edge which forms the ring

        3# no ring, two candidates found
        Either the deleted candidate edge break the ring, or there isn't a ring exsiting before we make deletion. For both of two situation, we return the second candidate

    */

    public int[] findRedundantDirectedConnection(int[][] edges) {
        int[] parents = new int[2000];
        List<int[]> candidates = new ArrayList<>();
        int[] can1 = new int[]{-1, -1}, can2 = new int[]{-1, -1};
        for (int[] edge : edges) {
            if (parents[edge[1]] != 0) {    // already has one parent
                candidates.add(new int[]{parents[edge[1]], edge[1]});  // happens firstly
                candidates.add(new int[]{edge[0], edge[1]});
                edge[1] = 0;    // delete second candidate
            } else {
                parents[edge[1]] = edge[0];
            }
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < 2000; i++)  parents[i] = i;

        for (int[] edge : edges) {
            if (edge[1] == 0)   continue;
            int child = edge[1], father = edge[0];
            if (child == findAncestor(parents, father)) {    // directed ring
                if (candidates.size() == 0) {   // ring found, no candidate, return current edge which forms the ring
                    return edge;
                } else {    // after we delete can2, still found ring, must be can1
                    return candidates.get(0);
                }
            }
            parents[child] = father;
        }

        // no ring, 2 candidates
        // either deleted one cause the ring
        // or it never has the ring, so we delete the last candidate
        return candidates.get(1);
    }

    public int findAncestor(int[] parents, int i) {
        while (parents[i] != i) {
            i = parents[i];
        }

        return i;
    }
}
```

