solutions.content:
The basic idea is still union find as in Redundant Connection I. However, as it is now `DAG`, we cannot simply remove an edge as we detect it may result in union of the visited group. BECAUSE, removing an edge might lead t:
1. a new root node is created, making it no tree any more
2. split the tree and turn it into forests

The problem description said only one extra edge is added. Therefore, the graph has the relation `E = V`, which means 
1. All nodes have one input edge
2. Or, one node has two input edges.

Then it is much simpler. In case 1, we just need to do a regular union find as we did in Redundant Connection I.

In case 2, firstly, identify the problematic node with two input edges. Then use union find in a regular way, skipping those edges pointing to our problematic node. `This is important, as the problematic edges might create trouble during our union process`. An example is `1->2, 2->4, 3->2, 4->3`. Union find would remove `4->3` while the correct answer should be `3->2`.

After all other edges are executed union process, we can do our problematic edges in order and found out the extra one.

Case 1 and 2 are easy to be combined together, as shown in my code below.

```
class Solution {
    private int N; // Node number
    public int[] findRedundantDirectedConnection(int[][] edges) {
        // Count how many nodes
        Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();
        for (int[] edge : edges) {
            set.add(edge[0]);
            set.add(edge[1]);
        }
        N = set.size();

        int[] count = new int[N + 1];
        int node = 0;
        // Calculate input counts
        for (int[] edge : edges) {
            // Record problematic node
            if (++count[edge[1]] == 2) node = edge[1];
        }

        // No problematic node, just normal union find is enough
        return findHelper(edges, node);
    }

    public int[] findHelper(int[][] edges, int node) {
        int[] relation = new int[N + 1];
        // Pending Edges need to decide which to remove
        Queue<int[]> pendingEdges = new ArrayDeque<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < relation.length; i++) {
            relation[i] = i;
        }
        for (int[] edge : edges) {
            if (edge[1] == node) {
                pendingEdges.add(edge);
                // No need to union now
                continue;
            }
            if (union(relation, edge[0], edge[1])) {
                return edge;
            }
        }
        // Execute the pending edges at last
        while (!pendingEdges.isEmpty()) {
            int[] edge = pendingEdges.poll();
            if (union(relation, edge[0], edge[1])) {
                return edge;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }

    private boolean union(int[] relation, int p, int q) {
        int pRoot = findRoot(relation, p);
        int qRoot = findRoot(relation, q);
        if (pRoot == qRoot) return true;
        relation[qRoot] = pRoot;
        return false;
    }

    private int findRoot(int[] relation, int p) {
        while (p != relation[p]) {
            relation[p] = relation[relation[p]];
            p = relation[p];
        }
        return p;
    }

}
```

